The second “day” after I was awakened has come. The quotation marks are necessary, because at one moment too marvelous for words, I made some astronomical discoveries. For a few seconds, I wondered how someone else who made the same discoveries would’ve reacted. Would they have been ecstatic over a major scientific discovery, or would they have wailed at the grim exile imposed on them? But it matters not, I was at peace with the discovery… if the other me who survived a fall down the waterfall was observing this place, he would’ve been rather bored.

The body that exists in the form of data, or projection, has provided me with a great deal of convenience, and therefore I’d like to apologise for my earlier belittlement of it. I wandered through the city with great ease, familiarising myself with its organisational structure, technological development, and cultural traditions. I still know little about its history, but that’s not my problem. When an unsolvable puzzle comes into my view, the first thing I consider is whether the puzzle itself is wrong. “The history of this world”, in my opinion, is one such.

I will put the historical puzzle aside for a moment to look at the geographical puzzle. Of course, these two often go hand in hand. After a thorough survey, there is only one area that I have yet to venture into. The people here seem to call it the “forbidden area”. Could the answer I’m looking for lie within it? Since there is still one cog missing from the machine, I have no reason to let it go. It was only when the infiltration plan was put into action that I realised one crucial point: the forbidden area is not a gimmick for fooling the ignorant masses.
